    bio: "Abu Abdullah Muhammad ibn Battuta was born in Tangier, Morocco, in 1304 into a family of Islamic legal scholars. At the age of twenty-one, he set out on the hajj to Mecca — a journey that would stretch into nearly three decades of continuous travel spanning some 75,000 miles, a distance unmatched by any known traveler until the age of steam. His route carried him through North Africa, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, Central Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, and China, as well as parts of Europe, making him one of the most widely traveled individuals in pre-modern history.\n\nIbn Battuta's travels were shaped by the vast interconnected world of fourteenth-century Islam, a civilization stretching from Spain to Indonesia that provided him with a common language, legal system, and network of hospitality wherever he went. He served as a qadi — an Islamic judge — in the Maldives and as an ambassador for the Sultan of Delhi, narrowly surviving shipwrecks, bandit attacks, and the Black Death along the way. His encounters ranged from the golden court of Mansa Musa's Mali Empire to the war-torn steppes of the Mongol khanates, providing an unparalleled eyewitness panorama of the medieval world.\n\nUpon his return to Morocco in 1354, the Marinid sultan commissioned a young scholar named Ibn Juzayy to record Ibn Battuta's experiences. The resulting work, known as the Rihla (\"The Journey\"), became one of the most important travel accounts ever written, offering detailed observations of societies, economies, and customs across three continents. Though some scholars have questioned whether he visited every place he claimed, the Rihla remains an indispensable source for understanding the medieval Islamic world and the remarkable networks of trade, faith, and culture that bound it together long before the European Age of Exploration."
