    summary: "On April 7, 1948, the constitution of the World Health Organization officially entered into force, establishing the first global institution dedicated to international public health. The WHO's founding document, drafted in 1946 at the International Health Conference in New York and signed by sixty-one nations, contained a revolutionary definition of health as \"a state of complete physical, mental and social well-being and not merely the absence of disease or infirmity.\" This expansive vision reflected the post-war conviction that health was a fundamental human right and that infectious diseases, which recognized no borders, demanded coordinated international action.\n\nThe creation of the WHO built upon decades of earlier efforts, including the International Sanitary Conferences of the nineteenth century and the Health Organization of the League of Nations. Headquartered in Geneva, Switzerland, the new agency immediately took on campaigns against malaria, tuberculosis, and sexually transmitted diseases, while working to standardize drug nomenclature and international health regulations. April 7 has been commemorated annually as World Health Day ever since, marking the moment when the nations of the world formally acknowledged that the health of every person, everywhere, was a matter of shared global responsibility.",
